are visible in the anterior neck region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves innervates the muscle responsible for these neck bands?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accessory nerve","Cervical branch of the facial nerve","Greater auricular nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Transverse cervical nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe muscle responsible for the vertical bands in the neck when frowning or tensing is the platysma. The platysma is a superficial muscle that extends from the chest and shoulder area up to the lower face. It is involved in facial expressions, such as frowning and creating tension in the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical branch of the facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the platysma. This branch is responsible for the motor supply to the muscle, allowing it to contract and create the observed neck bands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles, not the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for motor innervation to the muscles of the tongue, not the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater auricular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse cervical nerve\u003C/strong\u003E are sensory nerves and do not provide motor innervation to the platysma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The platysma is a superficial muscle located in the neck.","The platysma is innervated by the cervical branch of the facial nerve.","The platysma is involved in facial expressions, such as frowning and tension in the neck."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64211"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17967"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64211"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T09:16:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T09:17:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10681"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78862"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"